# Git workflow

This is an open source project. All changes must produce a clean, reviewable
commit history.

- **Break work into features.** Before starting a multi-part task, split it into
  logical units (a bug fix, a new tool, a docs update, a packaging change). Each
  unit gets its own commit — never one giant commit mixing unrelated changes.
- **Commit as you go.** After finishing and verifying each unit, commit it
  immediately before moving to the next. Do not leave a long session's work
  uncommitted.
- **Commit messages**: a short imperative summary line (e.g. "Fix model exports
  broken in GraphQL refactor"), plus a body when the why isn't obvious. No
  work-in-progress noise like "wip" or "fixes".
- **Nothing personal in the repo.** Never commit `.env`, API tokens, real course
  or institution IDs, or machine-specific paths. Placeholders belong in
  `.env.example`. If a secret was ever committed, flag it for rotation.
- **Everything documented.** A change to tools, config, or setup must update the
  README (and docstrings) in the same commit series.
- Do not push unless explicitly asked; commits are local by default.
